WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.600
[Music] Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger.&nbsp;
Today, we're going to be looking further&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.600 --> 00:00:20.440
at base 2 vexels, specifically focusing on the&nbsp;
arithmetic with base 2 vexels. We're trying to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:28.200
understand Hindu-Arabic numerals from a vexel&nbsp;
point of view. The idea is that we're just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:32.640
extending our understanding of vexels&nbsp;
a little bit to incorporate the idea&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:38.480
of numerals, and today we're going to be&nbsp;
concentrating on base 2 vexels. However,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.480 --> 00:00:45.520
it's not a big jump to go from the base&nbsp;
2 situation to the base 10 situation.

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:51.240
I remind you that this notion of vexel is a&nbsp;
very fundamental and flexible concept. It's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:57.000
multiset of singletons, and this actually&nbsp;
sheds new light on our earlier theory of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:04.120
polynumbers because vexels and polynumbers are&nbsp;
effectively pretty much the same thing. So, we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.120 --> 00:01:13.160
can kind of bring together two different kinds of&nbsp;
mathematical objects now into a single framework.

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:19.560
So, what is a vexel? Well, here's an example of&nbsp;
a vexel, V. It's a multiset, and it has a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.560 --> 00:01:27.160
these singletons in it. A singleton is just&nbsp;
a small list with one natural number in it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.160 --> 00:01:31.600
and these natural numbers that appear here are&nbsp;
primitive natural numbers. So, if we actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:38.800
looked more carefully or closely at this two,&nbsp;
we would see a little multiset of strokes:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:46.680
one, one. Alright, so that's a vexel, and&nbsp;
we've seen that we can also express it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:52.040
well, perhaps in this 'freeze' kind&nbsp;
of notation, as a column vector,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:52.040 --> 00:01:54.960
which is really effectively the same&nbsp;
thing as what we were talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:54.960 --> 00:02:01.800
earlier with polynumbers, where we have a&nbsp;
string of coefficients written vertically.

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:09.400
And I remind you that this polynumber also&nbsp;
corresponds to this polynomial kind of expression:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:09.400 --> 00:02:20.080
2 Alpha to the 0 + 0 Alpha + 3 Alpha squared +&nbsp;
Alpha cubed. It's worthwhile to really appreciate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:26.920
that a polynomial like this is now really being&nbsp;
associated with this arguably more fundamental&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:33.360
kind of data structure or situation. So, the&nbsp;
2 Alpha to the zero, which is just like two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:40.520
corresponds to these two zero singletons,&nbsp;
3 Alpha squared corresponds to these three&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:48.200
singletons of two, and this Alpha cubed&nbsp;
corresponds to this singleton of three.

00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:54.160
So, we're employing our multiset point&nbsp;
of view to understand polynumbers. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:54.160 --> 00:02:59.240
one of the big advantages of thinking about&nbsp;
things this way is that vexel arithmetic is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:05.760
very elemental because we're just working in&nbsp;
this very pleasant framework of multisets. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:13.760
addition, for example, is just multiset addition.&nbsp;
Here's a vexel, here's another vexel. To add this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:21.600
multiset and this multiset, we just put&nbsp;
all the singletons into a bigger multiset.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:28.000
Multiplication is also interestingly easy&nbsp;
in some ways; it's the multiset extension of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:33.800
the following essential product of singletons.&nbsp;
It's a rather novel product of singletons. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.800 --> 00:03:41.840
product of the singleton n with the singleton&nbsp;
m is, by definition, a singleton n + m. Then,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.840 --> 00:03:48.720
when we want to multiply two vexels, we&nbsp;
just have to employ this basic rule for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:57.920
each possible pair between the singletons in this&nbsp;
multiset and the singletons in that multiset. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:05.520
this 0 * this one is one, this 0 * this one&nbsp;
is one, this 2 * this one is the singleton&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:14.720
three, and then the corresponding&nbsp;
products are four, four, and six.

00:04:14.720 --> 00:04:22.440
This kind of multiplication corresponds to, on&nbsp;
the polynomial or polynumber side, the following:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.440 --> 00:04:30.520
so, this vexel here is really or can be thought&nbsp;
of as the polynumber 2 + Alpha squared. There's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:38.120
two zeros and a single two, so that corresponds&nbsp;
to 2 + Alpha squared. This one corresponds to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:38.120 --> 00:04:46.880
Alpha plus Alpha to the 4th, and when we multiply&nbsp;
those with the usual polynumber multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:56.120
we get 2 Alpha + Alpha cubed + 2 Alpha to the&nbsp;
4th + Alpha to the 6th. And that corresponds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.120 --> 00:05:02.760
to this product over here: 2 Alpha corresponds to&nbsp;
these two singletons, the Alpha cubed to that one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:08.480
the 2 Alpha to the fourth to these two, and&nbsp;
the Alpha to the sixth to the singleton six.

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:15.320
This technique of pinning polynomial or polynumber&nbsp;
arithmetic onto this more fundamental multiset&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:23.440
framework of vexels has another advantage: it&nbsp;
explains a former ambiguity that we had, kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:31.080
of a subtle issue that we never entirely resolved,&nbsp;
and that's the question of why adding zeros to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:38.560
polynumber doesn't change it. When we were looking&nbsp;
at polynumbers, basically lists of coefficients&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:45.800
written vertically, this polynumber here and this&nbsp;
polynumber were regarded as the same, even though&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:52.560
the actual number of entries here was different.&nbsp;
Somehow, adding a zero doesn't change things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:52.560 --> 00:05:59.040
and it was hard to say why that was except to&nbsp;
declare that that's how it was going to be.

00:05:59.040 --> 00:06:06.160
But now we can see that there's an explanation&nbsp;
for that in terms of the more fundamental objects&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:14.640
of the associated vexel. So, this thing here is&nbsp;
really a representation of this vexel: two zeros,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:14.640 --> 00:06:23.640
three twos, and a single three. When we look&nbsp;
at this thing as the fundamental object, well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:30.907
we can describe this in terms of a multiplicity&nbsp;
list in lots of ways. We can also say that there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:30.907 --> 00:06:36.880
are zero fours, zero fives, and zero sixes,&nbsp;
and so on, but it's really this object that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:43.760
is the fundamental thing. Note that there's no&nbsp;
ambiguity here, right? There's nothing we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.760 --> 00:06:51.760
add to this or take away, and it stays&nbsp;
the same; it's just this is the vexel.

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:57.360
For example, if you were programming, then at the&nbsp;
level of these lists, you would have to program&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.360 --> 00:07:03.120
in the fact that adding the zero doesn't&nbsp;
make a difference. But if your computer is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:10.360
working just with the multisets themselves,&nbsp;
then there's no need to even discuss that.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:17.520
With that review, we can now look at these&nbsp;
base 2 vexels. We take the idea of a vexel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:23.400
and we add a little bit to it to get a&nbsp;
new type of object called a base 2 vexel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:23.400 --> 00:07:30.880
and we'll denote the type by this expression: Vex&nbsp;
2, which corresponds to base two vexels. This is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:40.200
new type of vexel where we agree that we're going&nbsp;
to have a further kind of exchange rule applying.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.720 --> 00:07:49.040
This is a rule that allows us to exchange two&nbsp;
singletons of the same type, actually two equal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:58.640
singletons which appear in a multiset, with a&nbsp;
single singleton of the next higher number. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:07.280
the singleton n and the singleton n together can&nbsp;
be replaced with the single singleton n + 1. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:16.600
is supposed to be true for any natural&nbsp;
number, that means 0, 1, 2, and so on.

00:08:16.600 --> 00:08:24.360
For example, in Vex 2, here is a vexel, the same&nbsp;
one we've been thinking about: 2 0 3 1. Now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.360 --> 00:08:31.040
if we regard this as a vexel in Vex 2, in other&nbsp;
words, a base 2 vexel, then we are allowed to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:38.560
rewrite it because we can, for example, take&nbsp;
these two zeros here—this two really represents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:38.560 --> 00:08:46.000
two singleton zeros—and we can replace those&nbsp;
two singleton zeros with a singleton one. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:52.280
the two here can be replaced with the one here,&nbsp;
and otherwise, it doesn't change. Similarly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:59.440
we can take two of these, which would&nbsp;
be singleton twos in our actual list,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:09.520
and replace them with a singleton three, then&nbsp;
having altogether two singleton threes. At the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:15.960
next stage, we could take these two singleton&nbsp;
threes and replace them with a singleton four.

00:09:15.960 --> 00:09:24.720
In Vex 2, each of these is actually equal. These&nbsp;
are not equal as vexels, as ordinary vexels;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:32.920
they're clearly very different. But in Vex 2,&nbsp;
we agree that they are all the same object.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:42.560
This exchange rule allows us to have a lot of&nbsp;
different forms for the same base 2 vexel. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:49.840
we can also go the other way; we can exchange&nbsp;
two of one level for one of the next level,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:55.040
but we can also exchange one of one&nbsp;
level for two of the previous level.

00:09:55.040 --> 00:10:04.200
For example, here, our same 2 3 1, this base&nbsp;
2 vexel, can also be written as 2 0 5. What&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:12.120
we've done is we've taken this single one here,&nbsp;
which represents a 3 singleton, and converted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.120 --> 00:10:24.280
that 3 singleton to two 2 singletons. Now, there&nbsp;
were already three 2 singletons in our multiset,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:32.240
so now altogether there are five 2 singletons.&nbsp;
There's no reason why we couldn't do that again;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:32.240 --> 00:10:40.160
we could take those 2 singletons and take&nbsp;
each one and replace it with a pair of 1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:40.160 --> 00:10:49.480
singletons. So, the same base 2 vexel is&nbsp;
this, this one here, 2 1 0. And once more,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:49.480 --> 00:10:58.320
we could replace these 10 with 20 of&nbsp;
the previous ones, giving us just 2 2.

00:10:58.320 --> 00:11:04.920
So, we see we have quite a range of forms for&nbsp;
a base 2 vexel. We started with this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:08.080
the one that we've written down several&nbsp;
times already, and we saw that we could&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:15.360
kind of expand it out by replacing any twos with&nbsp;
one of the next ones. If we keep doing that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:22.960
eventually we get this expanded form&nbsp;
where there are only zeros and ones.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:28.240
This is usually what is thought of&nbsp;
when we think of a base 2 number.

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:31.720
Those of you from a computer science&nbsp;
background will naturally be thinking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:31.720 --> 00:11:36.040
that this is the object that I'm&nbsp;
going to be working with exclusively,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:43.360
but we're not going to work with these things&nbsp;
exclusively. Yes, this is a base 2 representation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:43.360 --> 00:11:48.160
but we are also going to allow ourselves&nbsp;
the flexibility that this base 2 vexel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:48.160 --> 00:11:55.120
can legitimately be rewritten in this way&nbsp;
or also in this way. Now, this is a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:55.120 --> 00:12:01.240
different kind of form. We could say this is the&nbsp;
compressed form, where we've pushed all of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:11.840
entries up so there are just zero singletons&nbsp;
here—there are really 2 2 zero singletons.

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:18.640
So, this is quite an interesting thing. We have&nbsp;
a base 2 vexel, and it can be written in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:18.640 --> 00:12:27.480
expanded form just with zeros and ones, or all&nbsp;
of the content can be pushed up here to give us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:27.480 --> 00:12:36.480
just a number with a certain number of zero&nbsp;
singletons. Maybe I should say there's a bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:42.680
of a qualification to what I just said, right?&nbsp;
So, I said we could take a typical base 2 vexel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:42.680 --> 00:12:49.200
and we could start pushing them all up and&nbsp;
getting this compressed form. That's certainly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:49.200 --> 00:12:56.640
true in the range of the smallish vexels&nbsp;
that we're considering here as examples,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:56.640 --> 00:13:03.600
but you could kind of imagine that if this&nbsp;
vexel here was, say, trillions and trillions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:10.840
of digits long, instead of having four entries,&nbsp;
there were trillions and trillions of entries,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:19.520
then pushing them all up and just getting a&nbsp;
compressed form is not at all trivial, okay?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:26.120
Because every time you take one at some level&nbsp;
and replace it with two of the previous level,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:26.120 --> 00:13:31.120
you're doubling the numbers, and so if you&nbsp;
have to go trillions up, then you're basically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:31.120 --> 00:13:36.600
taking powers of two, 2 to the trillion or 2&nbsp;
to the trillion to the trillion, and so on. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:36.600 --> 00:13:42.800
you very well might end up with a situation where&nbsp;
this number here is outside of the range that you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:42.800 --> 00:13:49.000
have because we are, I remind you, insisting&nbsp;
that each one of these entries here actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:58.440
be natural numbers, primitive natural numbers&nbsp;
that we can actually explicitly write down.

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:04.200
So, we're definitely looking at things a little&nbsp;
bit differently here. In the standard treatment&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:04.200 --> 00:14:11.880
of binary numbers, which is usually what base&nbsp;
2 vexels are called, they're always expressed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:20.360
in expanded form, and moreover, they're&nbsp;
almost always written horizontally. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:20.360 --> 00:14:28.320
usual convention is that the powers of two are&nbsp;
decreasing from left to right. So, the number 22,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:28.320 --> 00:14:37.480
or the natural number 22, is written in binary&nbsp;
as 10110, and in this representation, this zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:42.880
represents the number of ones, this represents&nbsp;
the number of twos, this the number of fours,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:42.880 --> 00:14:48.440
this the number of eights, and this the number of&nbsp;
16s. So, this is asserting that 22 can be built&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:48.440 --> 00:15:01.720
up by taking 2 + 4 + 16, and indeed 22 is 2 + 4 +&nbsp;
16. So, this is the binary representation of 22.

00:15:01.720 --> 00:15:07.440
This is the standard way of doing things, but&nbsp;
our notation is somewhat different because we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.440 --> 00:15:14.440
are writing this same thing vertically,&nbsp;
starting with the ones at the top,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.440 --> 00:15:21.440
what's usually called the ones at the top. So,&nbsp;
we wrote this as 0 1 1 0 1. The advantages of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:21.440 --> 00:15:26.440
writing things vertically rather than&nbsp;
horizontally are the same advantages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:32.920
that we get by thinking about polynumbers and&nbsp;
vertical objects rather than horizontal objects.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:40.480
This is made clear when we start thinking&nbsp;
about the arithmetic with base 2 vexels.

00:15:40.480 --> 00:15:45.600
So, let's think about that. Let's think about&nbsp;
addition with base 2 vexels. Suppose, for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:45.600 --> 00:15:57.680
that we're interested in the relation 22 + 13 =&nbsp;
35, okay? So, here is 22 written as a vexel, as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:57.680 --> 00:16:07.520
sort of polynumber in number form, and here is 13.&nbsp;
Let's just check this: so, this is 1, 0 twos, 4&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:18.560
and 8, this is 1 + 4 + 8, that is indeed 13, okay?&nbsp;
So, when we add these, well, it's not surprising;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:18.560 --> 00:16:27.080
we're just going to add component-wise. So, 2 +&nbsp;
1 is 3, 0 + 0 is 0, 3 + 1 is 4, and 1 + 1 is 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:35.680
and indeed this is the binary representation of&nbsp;
35, just written vertically. So, it's three 1s,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:35.680 --> 00:16:51.960
no twos, four 4s, and two 8s. So, this is 16 + 4&nbsp;
4s is another 16, that's 32 plus 3 is indeed 35.

00:16:51.960 --> 00:17:00.080
Now, another way of writing this is in expanded&nbsp;
form, okay? So, we could replace this base 2 vexel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:07.320
with its expanded form, which we've already seen:&nbsp;
0 1 1 0 1. This is the usual binary representation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:07.320 --> 00:17:15.800
of 22, but with the ones at the top—ones, twos,&nbsp;
fours, eights, 16s— increasing powers of two going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:24.280
down. This thing here is the binary representation&nbsp;
of 13; that's already in sort of expanded form.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:34.440
And now, if we apply the same rule here, we&nbsp;
would get 0 + 1 is 1, 1 + 0 is 1, 1 + 1 is 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:34.440 --> 00:17:42.440
0 + 1 is 1, and 1 plus this empty zero is 1. So,&nbsp;
we're still doing basically polynumber arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.440 --> 00:17:47.320
but now to get something in expanded form, we&nbsp;
would look at this 2 and think about replacing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:47.320 --> 00:17:54.080
it. So, replacing this 2 with a single&nbsp;
one of the next layer, this becomes zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:54.080 --> 00:18:00.120
and then this thing here becomes two. Then&nbsp;
I've done a few more steps, so I'm going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.120 --> 00:18:06.280
replace that two that's now there with another&nbsp;
one of these, giving us two of those, and then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:13.360
those two things are replaced with a single&nbsp;
one in the layer down, namely that one there.

00:18:13.360 --> 00:18:21.880
So, this thing here is equal to 1 1 0 1 1.&nbsp;
And let's just check that that's really the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:21.880 --> 00:18:32.640
same number in binary: this would be 1s, 2s, 4s,&nbsp;
8s, 16s, and 32s. So, this would be 1 + 2 + 32,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:32.640 --> 00:18:39.160
which is indeed 35. So, this is another&nbsp;
way of describing the addition of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:48.320
things in the base 2 vexel language. But yet&nbsp;
another way is just to write 22 + 13 = 35.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:48.320 --> 00:18:56.880
This is also a legitimate expression in base&nbsp;
2 vexels because these are also base 2 vexels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:56.880 --> 00:19:01.880
right? So, this base 2 vexel is the same as&nbsp;
this base 2 vexel, is the same as this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:07.120
and this one is the same as this one, is the same&nbsp;
as this one, and this one is the same as this one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:07.120 --> 00:19:15.640
is the same as this one. So, all of&nbsp;
these are valid computations in Vex 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:15.640 --> 00:19:22.200
even though in ordinary binary addition, we&nbsp;
would only really consider this plus this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:28.720
equaling this. Even this, as an intermediate&nbsp;
object, would usually not be allowed.

00:19:31.320 --> 00:19:38.400
There's a definite advantage, as we'll see, in&nbsp;
being a little bit more flexible about binary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:45.480
arithmetic and not insisting that everything&nbsp;
has to have zeros and ones. That's not the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:45.480 --> 00:19:51.400
essential feature of binary arithmetic.&nbsp;
The essential feature of binary arithmetic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:55.800
I'm suggesting, is captured&nbsp;
by the exchange condition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:55.800 --> 00:20:03.800
the fact that we are agreeing that two at&nbsp;
this level equals one at this level. That's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:03.800 --> 00:20:13.280
the crucial property of a base 2 vexel or,&nbsp;
in fact, of binary representation of numbers.

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:20.200
This line of reasoning becomes clearer when&nbsp;
we go to multiplication. Multiplication is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.200 --> 00:20:27.920
decidedly trickier than addition. So, let's&nbsp;
have a look at multiplication in this sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:27.920 --> 00:20:37.240
base two world. Let's look at 22 * 13, which is&nbsp;
286, and over here I just made that calculation&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:37.240 --> 00:20:42.160
so you can check. Here's how we multiply&nbsp;
22 by 13: we usually write them like that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:48.600
then draw the line, and we calculate 3 * 22. In&nbsp;
that case, it's 66; it's relatively easy to do,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:48.600 --> 00:20:53.400
and 1 * 22, that's in this case also&nbsp;
easy to do, so we put the 22 over there,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.400 --> 00:21:04.000
moved over one. Then we add 66 + 220 = 286. So,&nbsp;
relatively simple multiplication in that case.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:10.240
Now, how does the same thing look in binary?&nbsp;
The usual story in binary is to write 22 as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:10.240 --> 00:21:18.960
01101 and to write 13 as 1011, as we've seen,&nbsp;
and then essentially to do something like this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:18.960 --> 00:21:24.800
but sort of do it in binary. So, we take this&nbsp;
one—so one times all of this means we're just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:32.920
basically copying this out, just as we copied&nbsp;
the two when we multiplied by one. Then we move&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:39.120
over one to this place, and we have to multiply&nbsp;
zero times all of that—well, that's just a row of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:39.120 --> 00:21:44.280
zeros. And then the next one, there's a one here,&nbsp;
so we have to copy this thing again, but we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:44.280 --> 00:21:53.240
to move it over so that it's starting here now.&nbsp;
So, there's the 01101, and then there's one more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:53.240 --> 00:22:01.800
of them because we have to multiply by this one as&nbsp;
well. So, there's another copy right there: 01101.

00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:05.320
Alright, so now, just as before up&nbsp;
here, we're going to have to add up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:10.360
all these columns. Here we get a zero,&nbsp;
and here a one, and here a one, and here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:10.360 --> 00:22:16.320
a one. Here's the first place where something&nbsp;
interesting happens: we get a total of three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.320 --> 00:22:21.840
but in the traditional form, we're not allowed to&nbsp;
write three there. We have to expand that three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:21.840 --> 00:22:28.040
essentially think of it as 1 + 2. So, we&nbsp;
write the one for the one and the two as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.040 --> 00:22:33.920
a carry to give us a little one in the next&nbsp;
column representing the two. So, the total of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:40.280
three that we got here is divided into this&nbsp;
one here and this one in the next place up.

00:22:40.280 --> 00:22:46.880
Now, the sum in the next column is two, which&nbsp;
we write as 0 plus a carry of one. Then in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:46.880 --> 00:22:53.920
the next column, 1 + 1 is another two, which&nbsp;
is 0 plus a carry of one. Then 1 + 1 is two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:53.920 --> 00:23:01.160
which is 0 plus a carry of one, and finally,&nbsp;
the carry of one comes down. So, then our total&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:01.160 --> 00:23:10.760
is this number in binary, which is 0 ones, 2&nbsp;
twos, 4 fours, 8 eights, 16 sixteens, no 32s,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.760 --> 00:23:22.280
no 64s, no 128s, but a single 256. So, we see&nbsp;
that if we add these things up, we do get 286.

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:26.920
This is the standard story, but it's&nbsp;
actually quite a lot more subtle than&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:34.280
it usually appears because of the relatively&nbsp;
simple or small nature of the example we've&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:39.800
illustrated things with here, okay? If&nbsp;
we look at more complicated examples,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:39.800 --> 00:23:46.840
the story gets considerably more complicated,&nbsp;
and then it becomes clear that I think the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:46.840 --> 00:23:52.920
vertical approach that we're going to&nbsp;
show you now has some serious advantages.

00:23:52.920 --> 00:23:58.920
Okay, so now let me show you the same&nbsp;
multiplication operation but in a vertical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:58.920 --> 00:24:06.080
form, and I think you'll start to see the&nbsp;
advantages in thinking vertically. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:06.080 --> 00:24:15.320
so here is that first number, that was 22,&nbsp;
and here is 13. Let's multiply them in this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:15.320 --> 00:24:23.000
vertical fashion. Okay, so how could we&nbsp;
do that? Well, we could essentially do&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:27.400
the same kind of thing as we did before.&nbsp;
So, over here is going to be the sum,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:27.400 --> 00:24:32.600
and what we're going to do is multiply this thing&nbsp;
here first by one, and that just means basically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:32.600 --> 00:24:38.360
copying this thing over here. Then we're going to&nbsp;
multiply the same thing by zero, which basically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:38.360 --> 00:24:43.240
is a column of zeros. Then multiplying it by one&nbsp;
here, we're going to have the same thing, but now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:43.240 --> 00:24:51.760
it's displaced down two. When we multiply by this&nbsp;
one, it's the same thing but displaced one more.

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:56.360
So, this is really exactly the same&nbsp;
story that we had before, except that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:56.360 --> 00:25:02.720
these things are now going down columns as&nbsp;
opposed to going across rows—no difference,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:02.720 --> 00:25:10.360
okay? But now what we can do is think about these&nbsp;
various rows—this is just the same thing as what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:10.360 --> 00:25:17.520
was happening in the columns before—but we can&nbsp;
add up the things in these various rows. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:24.840
here's a zero, 1 + 0 is 1, 1 + 0 + 0 is 1, this is&nbsp;
1, here's a total of three, here's a total of one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:24.840 --> 00:25:30.320
here's a total of one, here's a total of one.&nbsp;
Because we're first of all having this flexible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:30.320 --> 00:25:39.280
approach about base 2 vexel arithmetic,&nbsp;
we're not bothered by having a three here.

00:25:39.280 --> 00:25:45.760
Okay, so in particular, if we wanted to, we could&nbsp;
stop the calculation—this is a legitimate output;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:53.240
this is a proper representation of the product&nbsp;
of these two things in base 2 vexel world. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:53.240 --> 00:25:58.760
we might consider this as an intermediate&nbsp;
calculation, and then we would carry this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:04.440
on to reduce it, and that would involve taking&nbsp;
this three—because that's the only one that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:04.440 --> 00:26:11.560
in this case bigger than one—and replacing that&nbsp;
three with a singleton one and then one of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:11.560 --> 00:26:16.680
next one. Well, one of the next one would&nbsp;
make that a two, and that two is going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:22.120
be replaced with one of those, which is going to&nbsp;
be—then there's two of them there and replaced&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:22.120 --> 00:26:28.240
with one of those. There'll be two of those&nbsp;
there and replaced with one of the final ones.

00:26:29.920 --> 00:26:37.000
So, this is the same kind of calculation&nbsp;
as before, but it has the advantage that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.000 --> 00:26:43.200
we're working horizontally here. So, suppose&nbsp;
we were working, for example, with numbers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:50.960
that had columns which were very long—maybe&nbsp;
hundreds or thousands of entries long—then&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:50.960 --> 00:26:57.320
these sums that are going to be going across&nbsp;
here are also going to be correspondingly long,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:57.320 --> 00:27:02.720
okay? When you're doing this kind of long thing,&nbsp;
it can be advantageous to work horizontally rather&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:09.080
than vertically because you have more room at the&nbsp;
end because you're going to be writing down a long&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:09.080 --> 00:27:16.560
number, okay? So, the number that you might get&nbsp;
at this level here is some number with 37 digits,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:16.560 --> 00:27:21.000
okay? It's nice to have room to write it&nbsp;
horizontally. If you're forced to work in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:21.000 --> 00:27:24.960
a column, then you have just this limited&nbsp;
amount of space at the bottom of the column&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:36.240
to write down the entry there. It's just&nbsp;
a notational difference, but in practice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:36.240 --> 00:27:43.240
if you actually did big multiplications,&nbsp;
you would find that there is a difference.

00:27:43.240 --> 00:27:48.280
So, this is all happening in Vexel 2—this is&nbsp;
arithmetic in base 2 vexels—and we can see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:55.400
that there's something pleasant about this&nbsp;
vexel approach to this binary operation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:55.400 --> 00:28:01.560
having this basic exchange property, which is&nbsp;
the essential feature that distinguishes vexel&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:09.120
arithmetic from base 2 vexel arithmetic&nbsp;
and allows us to deal with this kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:09.120 --> 00:28:15.760
intermediate calculation and indeed allows us to&nbsp;
collapse something like this if we want to. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:28.400
we collapse all of this to just be 286—the&nbsp;
single entry 286 and nothing else below.

00:28:28.400 --> 00:28:33.960
In our next video, I want to then&nbsp;
go to our main object of interest,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:33.960 --> 00:28:39.920
which are Hindu-Arabic numerals and the&nbsp;
arithmetic of Hindu-Arabic numerals. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:39.920 --> 00:28:47.280
it's much the same as what we've been doing now,&nbsp;
but the insights that we've gotten here will have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:47.280 --> 00:28:56.440
some effect on our approach to the way we set&nbsp;
out the arithmetic with Hindu-Arabic numerals.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:56.440 --> 00:29:02.200
In particular, we're going to be thinking about&nbsp;
multiplication in a little bit of a different way,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:02.200 --> 00:29:09.120
following this kind of lead. So, we're going&nbsp;
to be looking at Hindu-Arabic numerals and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:09.120 --> 00:29:14.600
really establishing a solid foundation&nbsp;
for them, independent of our primitive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:22.480
natural numbers. We're going to be looking&nbsp;
at multiplication with something of a new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:22.480 --> 00:29:37.920
orientation. I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger. Thanks for [Music] listening.

